The archival data forced many scholars, including [Robert Conquest](/Robert_Conquest), to revise their earlier estimates downward. While inconsistencies remain, the data is considered more reliable than the indirect sources used during the Cold War. These studies concluded that from 1928–53, about 14 million prisoners passed through Gulag labor camps and 4–5 million through labor colonies. These figures count convictions, not individuals, so the number of people is somewhat lower due to repeat sentences. Conversely, at times the official figures reflected camp capacity, not the actual population, which could be 15% higher.

### Impact

#### Culture

The Gulag's cultural impact was immense. It became a central part of modern [Russian folklore](/Russian_folklore). The songs of bards like [Vladimir Vysotsky](/Vladimir_Vysotsky) and [Alexander Galich](/Alexander_Galich_(writer)) described camp life. Words and phrases from the camps entered the vernacular. The memoirs of survivors like [Alexander Dolgun](/Alexander_Dolgun), [Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn](/Aleksandr_Solzhenitsyn), [Varlam Shalamov](/Varlam_Shalamov), and [Yevgenia Ginzburg](/Yevgenia_Ginzburg) became symbols of defiance, testaments to the courage of the imprisoned. The forced migration of artists to Siberia also led to a strange cultural renaissance in places like [Magadan](/Magadan), where the theater was on par with Moscow's.

#### Literature

Many eyewitness accounts have been published:
*   [Varlam Shalamov](/Varlam_Shalamov)'s *[Kolyma Tales](/The_Kolyma_Tales)* is a collection of short stories, considered a foundational text.
*   [Victor Kravchenko](/Victor_Kravchenko_(defector))'s *[I Chose Freedom](/I_Chose_Freedom_(book))* describes his encounters with forced labor camps.
*   [Anatoli Granovsky](/Anatoli_Granovsky)'s *I Was an NKVD Agent* includes his experiences as a prisoner in 1939.
*   [Julius Margolin](/Julius_Margolin)'s *A Travel to the Land Ze-Ka* was finished in 1947 but couldn't be published for years.
*   [Gustaw Herling-Grudziński](/Gustaw_Herling-Grudzi%C5%84ski)'s *A World Apart*, with an introduction by [Bertrand Russell](/Bertrand_Russell), is a harrowing personal account.
*   [Victor Herman](/Victor_Herman)'s *Coming out of the Ice* provides firsthand accounts of places Solzhenitsyn could only reference through others.
*   [Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn](/Aleksandr_Solzhenitsyn)'s *[The Gulag Archipelago](/The_Gulag_Archipelago)* was his magnum opus, but *[One Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich](/One_Day_in_the_Life_of_Ivan_Denisovich)* was the first work to expose the Gulag on a massive scale within the USSR.
*   [Slavomir Rawicz](/Slavomir_Rawicz)'s *[The Long Walk](/The_Long_Walk:_The_True_Story_of_a_Trek_to_Freedom)* tells the story of an escape from a camp in Yakutsk.
*   [János Rózsás](/J%C3%A1nos_R%C3%B3zs%C3%A1s), the "Hungarian Solzhenitsyn," wrote many books on the Gulag.
*   [Karlo Štajner](/Karlo_%C5%A0tajner), a Croatian communist, wrote *7000 days in Siberia*.
*   And many, many others, each a voice from the abyss.

#### Colonization

The city of [Vorkuta](/Vorkuta). A monument to forced settlement.

Soviet documents show the Gulag was intended to colonize remote areas. In 1929, the OGPU was tasked with this. The concept of "free settlement" was introduced. On April 12, 1930, [Genrikh Yagoda](/Genrikh_Yagoda) wrote:

> The camps must be transformed into colonizing settlements, without waiting for the end of periods of confinement... Here is my plan: to turn all the prisoners into a settler population until they have served their sentences.

Well-behaved prisoners who had served most of their term could be released to "free settlement" (*volnoye poseleniye*) outside the camp. Those who served their full term but were denied freedom of movement were also assigned to free settlement. Of the 40,000 people receiving state pensions in [Vorkuta](/Vorkuta_Gulag), an estimated 32,000 are former inmates or their descendants, trapped in the place of their imprisonment.

#### Economics

A 2024 study found that areas near Gulag camps that held a larger share of educated elites among their prisoners have since shown greater economic growth, demonstrating the long-run persistence of human capital across generations. An ironic legacy.

### Life after a term was served

Release was not freedom. Ex-prisoners were barred from many jobs. Hiding a past imprisonment was a crime. Former "politicals" were monitored by the "[First Departments](/First_Department)" (secret police outlets) at their workplaces. Many were forbidden from settling in large cities, a policy known as the [101st kilometre](/101st_kilometre).

### Memorials

Memorial in Astana, Kazakhstan, to the prisoners of the Akmola Female Labor Camp.
Map of Stalin's Gulag camps in the Gulag Museum in Moscow.
Memorial in [St. Petersburg](/St._Petersburg,_Russia).

Moscow and St. Petersburg have memorials made from boulders taken from the Solovki camp. Moscow's is on [Lubyanka Square](/Lubyanka_Square), site of the NKVD headquarters. People gather there annually on the [Day of Remembrance of the Victims of Political Repressions (October 30)](/Day_of_Remembrance_of_the_Victims_of_Political_Repressions). The State Gulag Museum in Moscow was founded in 2001 by survivor [Anton Antonov-Ovseyenko](/Anton_Antonov-Ovseyenko). In November 2024, the Gulag History Museum in Moscow was ordered to close for "fire safety" violations, part of the [Putin regime's](/Russia_under_Vladimir_Putin) broader crackdown on dissent. History, it seems, is a fire hazard.